abstract.para: This package contains photos and photo comparison documents for the Long Term Aquatic Monitoring (LTAM) program, in support of the Cedar River Watershed Habitat Conservation Plan for City of Seattle, Seattle Public Utilities, in King County, WA. At least (5) photos were taken at photo monitoring locations for all (25) monitoring sites for 2006-2017. Additional photos were taken to note other interesting features, such as side channels, fish barriers, bank erosion, and overview of the cross section line.
For more detailed information on the LTAM program, refer to the LTAM Methods and Reports package.

description.para: Five photos are required for all (25) monitoring sites (BOU, TOU, xs1, xs2, and xs3). Photos are taken mid channel, landscape view, holding the camera about 4 feet above ground, with the top half of the photo view above the stream and the bottom half of the photo view of the stream. There are errors in the dataset with missing photos and/or photos taken in portrait mode. For required photos, azimuth, photo view (US or DS), and if applicable, distance on cross section tape was recorded. Optional photos were also taken to note other interesting features, such as side channels, fish barriers, bank erosion, and overview of the cross section line. There was no required standard for taking optional photos.
Photos were downloaded and re-named the same day they were taken or the next day.
At the end of the field season, required photos were copied into a photo comparison document in Microsoft Word, where photos are arranged side by side for different years at the same location.

abstract.para: Data supports the long-term stream monitoring program within the Cedar River Habitat Conservation Plan (HCP). Data measures the overall ecological response of the watershed to HCP management activities to monitor stream health, document recovery from past water supply and land management operations, evaluate the success of stream habitat restoration projects, and help to identify any impacts of the City’s operations on stream ecosystems.

attribute.attributeDefinition: Main Sorting No, a number that is used to order records for the purposes of loading data, grouping data, or building formulas.
Method, an abbreviation or acronym whereas the method is a group of methods for a project or program and is described in a separate document.

Year Site ID, a number that is used to group data and is a conjugate of the 4 digit Sample Year and Site No. For example, 20062 refers to Sample Year 2006, Site 2, and 201022 refers to Sample Year 2010, Site 22. If the analysis is a Enter "999" for
User Name, as downloaded from Pendragon Forms or other electronic form. Also, "999" refers to not applicable; and "-999" refers to data that is required but is missing.
Timestamp, Date or Date and Time for when the data was collected and in format MM/DD/YYY hh:mm:ss.
Site No, a number that has been assigned to the site, whereas the same site number is used for repeat surveys.
Stream Name (short), the abbreviated or shortened stream name of the site that is being surveyed.

Reach Location, where where data was collected and is usually abbreviated (ie. "xs1" is cross section 1, "xs2" is cross seciton 2, "xs3: is cross section 3, "BOU" is bottom of unit and is the downstream boundary of the site, "TOU" is top of unit and is the upstream boundary of the site, "ch" is channel, "LB" is left bank when facing downstream, "RB" is right bank when facing downstream, etc. This attribute does not have domains because the abbreviation could be different depending on the site. Abbreviations are described more fully in the written protocol document.

Photo View, which is the direction in which the photo was taken (US, DS, LB to RB overview, etc.) Note that US refers to upstream, DS refers to Downstream, LB refers to Left Bank when facing downstream, and RB refers to Right Bank when facing downstream. This attribute does not have domains because the abbreviation could be different depending on the site. Abbreviations are described more fully in the written protocol document.
Photo Location and View, which is a conjugate of Method abbreviation, Site No, Stream Name, Reach Location, and Photo View. This attribute can be used to more efficiently sort and find records.

Photo No on Camera, which is the number as noted by the camara. Photo numbers with decimal points mean that more than 1 photo was taken, and after download, generally one of the photos was deleted. Photo No tends to be duplicated if photos are erasted from the camera.

Photo Azimuth, which is the angle in degrees, clockwise from North, as measured from a compass, and represents the photo direction. Must be qualified with Declination in order to determine if the azimuth is from magnetic north or true north (ie grid north). In decimal degrees.

attribute.attributeName: Distance on XS Tape For Photos (ft)
attribute.attributeLabel: Distance on XS Tape For Photos (ft)
attribute.attributeDefinition: Distance on Cross Section Tape, which is the number on a fiberglass reel tape that is spanning across the stream banks and is adjacent to or overhead of the observer when they take the photo. The observer records the number that is closest to them when they take the photo. Recording the number allows for repeat monitoring photos, as long as the cross section end points are known and can be related over time.
Comments, free form text for interesting or unusual sightings, problems, or issues.

attribute.attributeName: Photo No per Year Site ID (based on Timestamp)
attribute.attributeLabel: Photo No per Year Site ID (based on Timestamp)
attribute.attributeDefinition: Photo number per Year-Site Identifier, whereas photo number is sequentially ordered based on Timestamp. It may or may not be the same number as Photo Number, which tends to duplicate if photos are erasted from the camera.

Declination East, at the time the azimuth direction was measured. It is the angle between magnetic morth (the direction a compass needle points) and true north (ie grid north or geogrpahic north pole), Declination East is a positive number when magnetic north is east of true north. Note that Declination East changes about 0.5 degrees every 3 years in the North Bend, Washington vicinity. Declination is usually set on the backside of the compas by turning a small screw that shifts a black arrow to the desired degrees setting. If declination is not set properly on a compass, all azimuth readings will be incorrect. At the beginning of the field season, all observers should set their compass to the same degrees setting to reduce error between observers. Units in decimal degrees.
The names or initials of each person who participated in the survey.
